        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. B.</strong> <strong>Ventricular Septal Defect</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Based on the image and clinical description provided, <strong>the karyotype shows an abnormal characteristic of Trisomy 18, </strong>also known as <strong>Edwards syndrome</strong>. This is <strong>evidenced by the presence of three copies of chromosome 18</strong>. Children with Trisomy 18 often present with a range of clinical features,<strong> including developmental delays, failure to thrive, and distinctive craniofacial and hand features.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ventricular septal defect (VSD) is the most common cardiac anomaly associated with Trisomy 18</strong>. VSD is a <strong>hole in the wall separating the two lower chambers of the heart</strong>, which allows <strong>oxygen-rich blood to mix with oxygen-poor blood</strong>, potentially causing<strong> heart failure and other complications.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation</u>:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A. Atrial Septal Defect</strong> - While <strong>ASDs can occur in Trisomy 18</strong>, they <strong>are not as common as VSDs</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C. Mitral Valve Prolapse</strong> - This is not commonly associated <strong>with Trisomy 18</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D. Mitral Stenosis</strong> - This condition, characterized by <strong>the narrowing of the mitral valve</strong>, is also<strong> not commonly associated with Trisomy 18.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective</u>:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Trisomy 18 (Edward Syndrome) - </strong>The<strong> 2<sup>nd</sup> most common autosomal trisomy.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Clinical features include:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"><strong>Rocker bottom feet</strong></span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"><strong>Overlapping fingers</strong></span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"><strong>Clenched fist</strong></span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Short sternum</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Hypoplastic nails</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Hypoplastic nasal alae</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">IUGR</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Intellectual disability</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Microcephaly</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Hypertonia</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Prominent occiput</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Micrognathia</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Limited hip abduction</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Cleft lip / palate</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Most common cardiac defects:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"><strong>Ventricular septal defect (VSD)</strong></span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Atrial septal defect (ASD)</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">PDA</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Most common cause of death: Central apnea</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Prenatal screen lab findings:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Low alpha feto protein</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Low unconjugated estriol</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">Low beta hCG</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u></strong>: <strong>Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition, Chapter â€“ 98, Page No. 3024</strong></span></p>",
